english:
  title: Preface to a Collection of Poems Presented to Master Maeng
  author: Gwon Geun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Master Maeng of old took the examination in the Year of the Ox, and I followed in the Year of the Rooster—thus have I regarded him as an elder brother for many years now. His two sons, Sasung and Sagyeom, both studied under my tutelage. When the Minister of Rites oversaw the examinations, Sasung became the top graduate; when I later held the same position, Sagyeom passed the secondary examination. In this way, the entire Maeng family—father and sons, brothers all—became close companions of mine, bound by something far deeper than mere courtesy.

    The Master's character and conduct shine with clarity and integrity. Early in his career, he rose through the Hanlin Academy to become a Censor, earning the esteem of the scholarly community. Yet soon he resigned his office and returned to his village, tending fields to support his mother, lecturing on learning to instruct his sons, and finding joy in mountains and streams, wanting nothing of the world. When his parents passed, he observed three years of mourning at their tomb. Such was the height of his integrity.

    Our Sovereign, blessed with martial wisdom and the Mandate of Heaven, has founded our nation on virtue and able governance, especially valuing the welfare of the people. Thus was Master Maeng appointed magistrate of Jinju, where his administration bore evident fruit. Yet the Master would not bind his heart to legal codes nor bend his back for meager stipend. He set down the seal of office and withdrew to his hermitage, dwelling in ease as if to spend his remaining years thus.

    In the spring of that year, the royal procession visited the hot springs—the very region of the Master's retreat. There he beheld the imperial countenance and composed verses in praise of the Sovereign's virtue, which he humbly presented. Among the attending scholars, Minister Jeong of Sampong first claimed the rhyme for "great," then distributed the remaining rhymes among the assembled worthies. From the Left Prime Minister down through numerous officials, they produced both grand poems and brief verses—like spring clouds drifting, like strings of jade woven together—all singing of the Master's noble character.

    His son, now a court official, brought the collection to me requesting a preface. I was then bound for the Middle Kingdom and could not oblige. Upon my return the following year, the Master himself came to the capital to renew his request, which I could not refuse.

    I told him this: "Whether a gentleman of letters ventures forth or remains in retreat, the Way admits no fixed rule—only that one's choice accord with the times and with righteousness. When the world's order decays and power-hungry villains seize control, when corrupt officials advance shamelessly, then the wise and virtuous withdraw to distant solitude, their light hidden in desolate places. But when Heaven's mandate flourishes and governance grows fair, then such men shake out their robes and ascend to court, vying to display their talents for the benefit of all people. Thus must the noble constantly observe whether the age tends toward corruption or renewal, and conduct themselves accordingly.

    In former times, you discerned that the age was dark and wisely retreated, counting wealth and rank as chaff, treating high office as mere dust. Your lofty bearing and distant footprints were indeed beyond our reach. But now a sage-king reigns above, worthy ministers fill the court, and every office has found its proper man. Yet still we fear that scholars of hidden talent and aged sages, seeking no worldly renown, may languish in mountain caves or humble dwellings. We cast our nets wide and extend urgent summons, so keen is our desire for the worthy.

    This is the very moment for gentlemen of letters to emerge and accomplish great things. Can the Master remain forever in hiding? Let him bring his learning to the court, display his abilities, establish his achievements in this time. Should he not ascend to offer counsel in the halls of government and join in songs of wise rule, yet still observe the art of governance and compose verses of elegance to adorn our glorious age—verses to be sung in ancestral temples and royal banquets, rivaling the "Deer Song" and "Clear Temple" of old—would this not be magnificent? How could we allow such a man to cower in forests and creep through furrows, merely delighting in occasional imperial tours?

    I foresee the day when recluses like yourself come forth, their brilliance radiating to illuminate this age of great peace and perfect governance. The Master should seize this hour with resolve."
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: 'Hanlin Academy (翰林): A prestigious institution in classical Chinese bureaucratic systems, serving as a body of scholars and literary officials.'
  - key: ''
    value: The chronological references (Years of the Ox and Rooster, etc.) follow the traditional sexagenary cycle used in East Asian calendars.
  - key: ''
    value: '"Deer Song" and "Clear Temple": Classical poems in the Book of Poetry, exemplars of auspicious court poetry.'
  - key: ''
    value: The Master's withdrawal from office to observe three years of mourning reflects Confucian filial piety, one of the highest virtues in classical society.
